{
  "texts": [
    "We show that rhetorical citations benefit community health by redistributing focus from a small stable set of elite papers to a more dynamic set of high-to mid-quality ones that are rhetorically useful.",
    "ResultsWe present results from the more realistic heterogeneous agents models and for completeness report homogeneous agents results in Supplementary Information (Supplementary Methods).",
    "To test whether rhetorical citations benefit the three metrics of community health, one-tailed OLS regressions were performed without multiple comparisons.",
    "Data has been tested to ensure that they meet the assumptions of t-test.",
    "Panel d shows that, at the end of 1000 timesteps, quality, and citations are more correlated (+2.5%) in the full model than in either of the null models."
  ]
}